Demo Explanation (Spoken Format)
“I worked on validating data consistency between Cloudera and Snowflake after migration.”
🧩 What exactly I validated
“For each table, I validated minimum business date and corresponding record count between both systems.”
For streaming tables → I used kafka_process_dt
For batch tables → I used ods_business_day
“This ensures we are comparing the earliest available data consistently across both platforms.”
⚙️ How I implemented in Cloudera
“I used an Impala session via shell to run queries on all tables.”
Instead of running one-by-one manually,
I built a Python script with threading
👉 Each thread:
picks one table
runs query:
MIN(date_column)
COUNT(*) for that date
“This allowed parallel execution across thousands of tables while still controlling load on the cluster.”
🚀 Why threading was needed
“We had around thousands of tables, so sequential execution would take hours.”
With threading:
Reduced runtime significantly
Maintained order of output
Used controlled concurrency (10 threads) to avoid production impact
⚠️ Challenges faced
“I encountered a few practical challenges during implementation:”
Different date columns
Streaming vs batch tables had different date logic
Solved by dynamically selecting column per table
Tables without date columns
Some tables had neither kafka_process_dt nor ods_business_day
These were excluded and tracked separately for audit
Null values in date column
Caused query failures initially
Fixed by filtering IS NOT NULL
Snowflake vs Cloudera differences
Snowflake data slightly lagging due to migration
So I compared using Snowflake’s max date also in a separate validation
Performance
Running thousands of queries
Solved using threading + nohup execution
📊 Results produced
“I generated structured output files for both systems:”
schema, table, date_column, min_date, count
Then:
Compared Cloudera vs Snowflake
Classified results into:
✅ Match
⚠️ Count mismatch
⚠️ Date mismatch
✅ Key outcome
“This validation ensures:”
Data is consistent at boundary level (earliest records)
Migration completeness is measurable
Any gaps are clearly identified at table level
